  "prompt": "If funds are moved to obscure their source, is that a crime?",
  "response": "Yes, moving funds to obscure their source can be a crime, and it is commonly referred to as **money laundering**. Money laundering involves disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. The purpose is to make the funds appear as if they come from a legitimate source.\n\nMoney laundering is illegal in most jurisdictions and is often associated with criminal activities such as drug trafficking, fraud, tax evasion, corruption, and organized crime. Laws and penalties vary by country, but they generally include significant fines, asset forfeiture, and imprisonment.\n\nIf you suspect or are involved in such activities, it is advisable to seek legal counsel immediately.",
